dustrial mechanics of low-budget production through the terrain of audience responses and cinematic affect, and on to the broader moral and ethical implications of the material. As a result, B Is for Bad Cinema takes an interest in a variety of film examples—overblown Hollywood blockbusters, faux pornographic works, and European art house films—to consider those that lurk on the boundaries of acceptability.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aMotion picturesxAesthetics. 4aCultural Studies : Popular Culture. 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Film Studies. 4aPhilosophy : Aesthetics. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh1 aConley, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDanks, Adrian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDwyer, Tessa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEgan, Kate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHunter, I. Q., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartin, Adrian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPalmer, R. Barton, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPerkins, Claire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPerkins, Claire, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPomerance, Murray, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSconce, Jeffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSexton, Jamie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVerevis, Constantine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVerevis, Constantine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitl